You can update your calendar using either [Calendar.Events.update()](https://developers.google.com/calendar/v3/reference/events/update) or [Calendar.Events.Patch()](https://developers.google.com/calendar/v3/reference/events/patch). The difference between these two is that in update, all the data specified in your call will be set to your event (and the rest will be unset) whereas using `Patch()` only the data that you specify is modified (and the of the event&#39;s properties are left as they were).
You can see an example  below:

```js
function calUpdate() {
  var startSearch = new Date(new Date().setDate(new Date().getDate()+4));
  var endSearch = new Date(new Date().setDate(new Date().getDate()+9));
  var calendar = CalendarApp.getCalendarById(&#39;&lt;YOUR_CALENDAR_ID&gt;&#39;);
  var foundEvents = calendar.getEvents(startSearch, endSearch,{search:&quot;production meeting&quot;});
  var event = foundEvents[0];

  var patch = {
    attachments: [{
      &#39;fileUrl&#39;: &#39;&lt;YOUR_FILE_URL&gt;&#39;,
      &#39;title&#39;: &#39;Test&#39;
    }]
  }
  
  var eventId = event.getId().split(&quot;@google.com&quot;)[0];
  Calendar.Events.patch(patch, &#39;primary&#39;, eventId, {&quot;supportsAttachments&quot;: true});
}
```

Bear in mind that at the moment, it is only supported to attach Drive files.

